## Run complete — 002G2 Admin User Action Permission Granularity ✅

**What the slice fixed:** The admin user-management API (built in 002G) treated *any one* of `users.user.create/update/disable` as full user-management authority. `auth-permissions.md` §12.1 defines those as four distinct, risk-rated permissions, so a future limited role could suspend users or reassign roles/teams with an unrelated grant.

**What I changed (backend only, TDD):**
- Split session authentication (`401`) from authorization (`403`) in `admin_views.py`, and gave each action its own required permission set in `admin_users.py`:
  - **List/detail read** → `users.user.read` OR any write user-admin permission
  - **Role assignment / team add/remove** → `users.user.update`
  - **Suspend** → `users.user.disable`; **restore to active** → `users.user.update` (`set_status` authorises *after* reading the target status)
- Forbidden partial-permission writes now fail closed with `403 PERMISSION_DENIED` **before any mutation** — no `AuditLog` row, no session revocation.
- Removed the now-dead `has_manage_users_permission` helper (no-dead-code rule).

**Key judgement call (A-015):** The seeded `system_admin` role holds create/update/disable but **not** `users.user.read`, so a strict read-only gate would lock out the platform's only user-admin. Read accepts the write permissions as a documented compatibility fallback — no invented seed grant. Recorded in ASSUMPTIONS.md.

